# Animation

Use `Dali::Ui::View::Animate` with `Dali::Animation` to add timed motion to `dali-ui` views.

## Table of Contents

- [Animate a View](#animate-a-view)
- [Reuse Motion with Animation Specs](#reuse-motion-with-animation-specs)
- [Control Playback](#control-playback)
- [Coordinate Timing, Delays, and Easing](#coordinate-timing-delays-and-easing)
- [Use Label Animation APIs](#use-label-animation-apis)

## Animate a View

`Dali::Ui::View` is the application-facing object model for `dali-ui`. Start with a `Dali::Animation`, ask the view for a `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationBridge` through `Dali::Ui::View::Animate`, then chain typed animation operations such as `Opacity`, `PositionY`, `ScaleX`, and `ScaleY`.

`Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationBridge` is a lightweight bridge that applies typed animation entries to the supplied `Dali::Animation` while keeping application code focused on `Dali::Ui::View` rather than raw actor property calls.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

void FadeAndLift(Dali::Ui::View view)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.6f);

  view.Animate(animation)
    .Opacity(0.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.4f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT))
    .PositionY(-32.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.6f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT));

  animation.Play();
}
```

Use the `By` methods when the motion should be relative to the view's current value.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

void Nudge(Dali::Ui::View view)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.25f);

  view.Animate(animation)
    .PositionXBy(24.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.25f))
    .OpacityBy(-0.2f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.25f));

  animation.Play();
}
```

For common view motion, prefer the typed `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationBridge` methods over raw property animation. The bridge maps transform and opacity methods to inherited actor properties such as `Dali::Actor::Property::OPACITY`, `Dali::Actor::Property::POSITION_X`, `Dali::Actor::Property::POSITION_Y`, `Dali::Actor::Property::SCALE_X`, and `Dali::Actor::Property::SCALE_Y`, but application examples should stay View-first.

## Reuse Motion with Animation Specs

Use `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec` when the same animation recipe should be applied to multiple views or replayed later. A spec stores typed entries; `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec::ApplyTo` applies those entries to a concrete `Dali::Animation` and `Dali::Ui::View`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec CreateAppearSpec()
{
  return Dali::Ui::View::NewAnimationSpec()
    .Opacity(1.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.3f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT))
    .ScaleX(1.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.3f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT))
    .ScaleY(1.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.3f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT));
}

void PlayAppear(Dali::Ui::View view, const Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec& spec)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.3f);
  spec.ApplyTo(animation, view);
  animation.Play();
}
```

A spec is useful for consistent interaction states. For example, a pressed state can move and fade by relative amounts, while the release state can restore absolute target values.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec CreatePressSpec()
{
  return Dali::Ui::View::NewAnimationSpec()
    .PositionYBy(6.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.12f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT))
    .OpacityBy(-0.1f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.12f));
}

void ApplyPress(Dali::Ui::View view)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.12f);
  Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec spec = CreatePressSpec();

  spec.ApplyTo(animation, view);
  animation.Play();
}
```

## Control Playback

`Dali::Animation` owns playback state. After adding entries through `Dali::Ui::View::Animate` or `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec::ApplyTo`, use `Play`, `Pause`, `PlayAfter`, or `PlayFrom` to control when the animation runs.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

class ViewMotion
{
public:
  void Build(Dali::Ui::View view)
  {
    mAnimation = Dali::Animation::New(0.5f);

    view.Animate(mAnimation)
      .Opacity(1.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.5f))
      .PositionX(120.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.5f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT));
  }

  void Start()
  {
    mAnimation.Play();
  }

  void StartAfterDelay()
  {
    mAnimation.PlayAfter(0.2f);
  }

  void Pause()
  {
    if(mAnimation.GetState() == Dali::Animation::PLAYING)
    {
      mAnimation.Pause();
    }
  }

  void ReplayFromHalfway()
  {
    mAnimation.PlayFrom(0.5f);
  }

private:
  Dali::Animation mAnimation;
};
```

Use loop settings for repeating motion. `Dali::Animation::SetLooping` enables looping, `Dali::Animation::SetLoopCount` sets a loop count where `0` repeats forever, and `Dali::Animation::SetLoopingMode` chooses restart or auto-reverse behavior. Do not combine `SetLooping` and `SetLoopCount` for the same animation because each resets the other setting.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

Dali::Animation CreatePulse(Dali::Ui::View view)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.8f);

  view.Animate(animation)
    .ScaleX(1.08f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.4f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT))
    .ScaleY(1.08f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.4f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT));

  animation.SetLooping(true);
  animation.SetLoopingMode(Dali::Animation::AUTO_REVERSE);
  animation.Play();

  return animation;
}
```

## Coordinate Timing, Delays, and Easing

Each `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationBridge` and `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec` entry accepts a `Dali::Ui::Duration`, an optional `Dali::AlphaFunction`, and an optional delay. `Dali::Ui::Duration` stores seconds and can report values through `InSeconds` and `InMilliseconds`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

void StageEntrance(Dali::Ui::View title, Dali::Ui::View panel)
{
  Dali::Ui::Duration quick(0.2f);
  Dali::Ui::Duration normal(0.45f);

  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(normal.InSeconds());

  title.Animate(animation)
    .Opacity(1.0f, quick, Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT));

  panel.Animate(animation)
    .Opacity(1.0f, normal, Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT), Dali::Ui::Duration(0.1f))
    .PositionY(0.0f, normal, Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT), Dali::Ui::Duration(0.1f));

  animation.Play();
}
```

`Dali::AlphaFunction` controls how progress is mapped over time. The default `Dali::AlphaFunction()` is linear. Use built-in values such as `Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN`, `Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT`, and `Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT` for common UI motion curves.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

void CompareCurves(Dali::Ui::View slowStart, Dali::Ui::View smooth)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.5f);

  slowStart.Animate(animation)
    .PositionX(80.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.5f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN));

  smooth.Animate(animation)
    .PositionX(80.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.5f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT));

  animation.Play();
}
```

## Use Label Animation APIs

Labels can use the same view animation concepts through `Dali::Ui::LabelAnimationBridge` and `Dali::Ui::LabelAnimationSpec`. These `dali-ui` animation symbols extend the view animation surface with label-specific animation methods while preserving the fluent chaining style.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

void FadeLabel(Dali::Ui::Label label)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.3f);

  label.Animate(animation)
    .Opacity(0.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.3f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT));

  animation.Play();
}
```

Use `Dali::Ui::LabelAnimationSpec` when a label motion recipe should be reused in the same way as a `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

Dali::Ui::LabelAnimationSpec CreateLabelRevealSpec()
{
  return Dali::Ui::Label::NewAnimationSpec()
    .Opacity(1.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.25f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT))
    .PositionY(0.0f, Dali::Ui::Duration(0.25f), Dali::AlphaFunction(Dali::AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT));
}

void RevealLabel(Dali::Ui::Label label)
{
  Dali::Animation animation = Dali::Animation::New(0.25f);
  Dali::Ui::LabelAnimationSpec spec = CreateLabelRevealSpec();

  spec.ApplyTo(animation, label);
  animation.Play();
}
```
